The paper deals with synchronization constructs in multi-socket architectures, which are typically studied in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper specifically focuses on the Linux kernel's qspinlock, which falls under the Operating Systems (cs.OS) sub-category. The paper also presents a new lock that requires minimal memory, which could be of interest to researchers in the Architecture (cs.AR) sub-category. The paper's focus on synchronization constructs and performance evaluation could also place it in the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. Finally, the paper's integration of the new lock in the Linux kernel could make it relevant to researchers in the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
